.TH "MouseEvent.clientX" "JS" "June 10, 2024" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
MouseEvent.clientX \- MouseEvent: clientX property
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]clientX\f[B]\f[R] read\-only property of the
\f[CR]MouseEvent\f[R] interface provides the horizontal coordinate
within the application\[cq]s viewport at which the event occurred (as
opposed to the coordinate within the page).
.PP
For example, clicking on the left edge of the viewport will always
result in a mouse event with a \f[CR]clientX\f[R] value of \f[CR]0\f[R],
regardless of whether the page is scrolled horizontally.
.SH VALUE
A \f[CR]double\f[R] floating point value in pixels.
.SH EXAMPLES
This example displays your mouse\[cq]s coordinates whenever you trigger
the \f[CR]mousemove\f[R] event.
.SS HTML
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]p\f[R]>Move your mouse to see its position.</\f[B]p\f[R]>
<\f[B]p\f[R] id=\[dq]screen\-log\[dq]></\f[B]p\f[R]>
.EE
.SS JavaScript
.IP
.EX
\f[B]let\f[R] screenLog = document.querySelector(\[dq]#screen\-log\[dq]);
document.addEventListener(\[dq]mousemove\[dq], logKey);

\f[B]function\f[R] logKey(e) {
  screenLog.innerText = \[ga]
    Screen X/Y: ${e.screenX}, ${e.screenY}
    Client X/Y: ${e.clientX}, ${e.clientY}\[ga];
}
.EE
